The new message comes amid one of the most intense performance-review cycle=
s in the company=E2=80=99s history, in which Meta managers are ratcheting u=
p pressure on the workforce. It follows Meta=E2=80=99s layoff of 13% of its=
 workforce, or 11,000 people, in November. Now, as fears of a recession mou=
nt, some employees worry more job cuts could be on the horizon.

This is semantically irritating =E2=80=94=C2=A0shouldn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cm=
eets all expectations=E2=80=9D include meeting the meta-expectation that yo=
u exceed the other expectations? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but practically reasonable;=
 the message is =E2=80=9Cyou have to blow us away every day if you want to =
keep working here,=E2=80=9D which is a nice thing to aspire to.=C2=A0(Also =
I mean, fine, grade inflation is everywhere.) Incidentally Meta=E2=80=99s h=
ighest performance grade (above =E2=80=9Cexceeds expectations=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cgreatly exceeds expectations=E2=80=9D) is =E2=80=9Credefines expec=
tations,=E2=80=9D which I am not sure is entirely a good thing. =E2=80=9CTh=
is person makes me expect things I had never expected before=E2=80=9D: Coul=
d go either way.
I was going to make a joke about how it is hard to run a company where you =
fire=C2=A0your=C2=A0average employees every year, but actually that seems p=
lausible=C2=A0in big tech in 2023? Like, you have 90,000 employees, you ran=
k them, you fire the bottom 50,000, now you have 40,000 employees, you rank=
 them next year, you fire the bottom 25,000, now you have 15,000 employees,=
 you rank them the next year, you fire the bottom 8,000, etc., I don=E2=80=
=99t know, the Elon Musk Twitter experience teaches that you can repeatedly=
 fire half of your workforce and it might be fine, or fine-ish.=C2=A0
Speaking of the Elon Musk Twitter experience, Twitter is   selling off its =
office espresso machines? And here is a  New York Magazine cover story abou=
t Musk=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cextremely hardcore=E2=80=9D regime at Twitter tha=
t I found kind of upsetting to read? Like I feel like there are, in the wor=
ld, cushy jobs, and there are hardcore jobs, and some people want hardcore =
jobs building rockets for SpaceX and other people want cushy jobs selling a=
ds at Twitter. And if you start a company, you can start a hardcore company=
 or a cushy company or something in between, but if there=E2=80=99s an alre=
ady-existing large public company it is very hard to transition it from one=
 end of the scale to another.
  [8]
=C2=A0When you select yourself into a cushy job and it suddenly, through th=
e market for corporate control, becomes hardcore, that=E2=80=99s pretty rou=
gh on you. Apparently thousands of Twitter employees who six months ago wer=
e working reasonable hours for good pay with great snacks have decided =E2=
=80=9Cokay guess I=E2=80=99ll be sleeping at the office from now on,=E2=80=
=9D but presumably thousands of others had arranged their lives in such a w=
ay that they had to go home and see their families at night? I just don=E2=
=80=99t understand how you can take a cushy company=C2=A0and turn it hardco=
re without replacing all the employees and giving the new employees somethi=
ng inspiring to be hardcore about.

