  [1] An important answer that I am not going to discuss further here, but =
that is often important in real life, is taxes. Generally, in the US, compa=
nies can deduct the interest they pay on debt, but they can=E2=80=99t deduc=
t dividends to shareholders. My dumb toy schematic doesn=E2=80=99t mention =
interest explicitly, but in fact the deductibility of interest is a major e=
xception to Modigliani-Miller and part of the reason that a lot of companie=
s use debt financing.=20


  [2] This stuff is all in the ballpark of right, for US banks, but don=E2=
=80=99t take it too literally. Actual capital requirements are more nuanced=
, and there are backup regimes so that you can't really buy T-bills with ze=
ro capital.=20


  [3] Friedman and Kraus=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CEngineering the Financial Crisi=
s=E2=80=9D is a book on related topics. And here is a  US Government Accoun=
tability Office report from 2016 titled =E2=80=9CMortgage-Related Assets: C=
apital Requirements Vary Depending on Type of Asset.=E2=80=9D


  [4] Technically FTX appointed a new chief executive officer, John Ray, mo=
ments *before* filing for bankruptcy, but it was part of the same process.


  [5] In auto-downloading PDF format, sorry. You can find it on  the docket=
 site under =E2=80=9CJanuary 17, 2023 =E2=80=93 Maximizing FTX Recoveries: =
Management & Committee Meeting Presentation.=E2=80=9D


  [6] It also describes a different setting =E2=80=94 that allowed a =E2=80=
=9Csmall group of individuals=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cmove assets (crypto) by =
accessing the private keys to initiate a direct on-chain transaction.=E2=80=
=9D Obviously one simple way to steal customer money from a crypto exchange=
 would be to use the exchange=E2=80=99s private keys to send all of its cry=
pto to your own wallet, but that doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be a big part of t=
he FTX story. Though there seems to have been some draining of accounts sho=
rtly after the bankruptcy filing, and =E2=80=9CInvestigation is underway to=
 determine whether any off-ledger misuse of such access occurred.=E2=80=9D


  [7] Also I=E2=80=99m not sure that=E2=80=99s what happened; the presentat=
ion doesn't get into details but it=E2=80=99s conceivable that FTX US=E2=80=
=99s situation was, like, $181 million of crypto customer balances, $50 mil=
lion of dollar customer balances, $181 million of crypto assets and $400 mi=
llion of cash, exactly matching the customer exposures but with some extra =
cash cushion. That doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be what the FTX presentation imp=
lies, but it doesn=E2=80=99t quite rule it out either.


  [8] Are there examples of a company jarringly transitioning from extremel=
y hardcore to extremely cushy? I am tempted to say =E2=80=9Cinvestment bank=
s after 2008,=E2=80=9D but I know that=E2=80=99s not true. Presumably some =
hard-charging startups have been bought by big companies and then started c=
oasting, but that=E2=80=99s not really the same.


