<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talk from <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/30288429.269516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDcvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1sb2=
9raW5nLWZvci10ZXRoZXItcy1tb25leT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTE4MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fb=
WVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMTgmdXRtX2Nh=
bXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB24bb5e4b" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> time</a=
> to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30288429.2695=
16/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMjgv=
ZnR4LXMtYmxvY2tmaS1yZXNjdWUtZGlkbi10LXdvcms_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExODIzX01PTkVZU1R=
VRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMT=
E4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa2543315" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> time</a> around here about the cash-flow-slicing business. The way it g=
oes is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have some business that will make=
 somewhere between $75 and $150 next year.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">You can sell it to one owner who gets=C2=A0the cash flows from the=
 business. If it makes $75, she gets $75; if it gets $100, she gets $100; i=
f it gets $150, she gets $150; etc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">Her ownership stake is worth some=C2=A0amount of money, presumably betwee=
n $75 and $150. Let=E2=80=99s say it=E2=80=99s $100. She would pay $100 for=
 this ownership stake.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Or</em>, you can divide up the cash flows. A senior bondholder gets the=
 first $50 of cash flows: If the business makes $75, she gets $50; if it ma=
kes $150, she gets $50. A junior bondholder gets the next $30: If the busin=
ess makes $75, he gets $25; if it makes $80 or $100 or $150, he gets $30. A=
nd then a=C2=A0shareholder gets whatever is left, whatever the business mak=
es above $80: If it makes $75 or $80, she gets zero; if it makes $100, she =
gets $20; if it makes $150, she gets $70.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Here, the senior bond is much <em>safer=C2=A0</em>than the un=
itary ownership claim: In Steps 1-3, the owner puts up $100 and could lose =
money (get back $75) or make money (get back $150) or somewhere in between,=
 but in Step 4, the senior bondholder always gets back $50. The junior bond=
 is also safer than total ownership, with less variance in its returns: It =
gets back $30 in almost every case, unless things go quite=C2=A0badly. The =
shareholder in Step 4, though, takes much more risk than the total owner in=
 Steps 1-3: The total owner always gets back at least $75, while the levere=
d shareholder here might get back $0.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">You can sell the senior bond=C2=A0<em>plus </em>the junior bond=C2=A0<e=
m>plus=C2=A0</em>the shares for some amount of money, presumably between $7=
5 and 150. Let=E2=80=99s say it=E2=80=99s $105.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">$105 is more than $100 so this is a good trade. You have crea=
ted $5 of value by slicing the cash flows.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is one of the main things that happens in=
 finance. It describes how companies work =E2=80=94=C2=A0they issue debt an=
d equity, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and your mortgage, and banks. In its purest f=
orm, where you just have some set of cash flows and you slice them up into =
junior and senior claims, it is often called =E2=80=9Csecuritization,=E2=80=
=9D or=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cstructured finance.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why would this work? Why would the sliced-up c=
laims (senior bonds, junior bonds, shares) be worth more ($105) than a sing=
le unitary claim ($100)? There is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/30288429.269516/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvTW9=
kaWdsaWFuaSVFMiU4MCU5M01pbGxlcl90aGVvcmVt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0265325d=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;"> a famous theorem</a> saying that it shouldn=E2=80=99t work, that=
 the value of the cash flows shouldn=E2=80=99t depend on how you slice them=
 up. But of course people do slice them up.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> At least sometimes, it seems, there is more demand for a very safe cas=
h flow=C2=A0<em>plus=C2=A0</em>a very risky cash flow=C2=A0than there is fo=
r a single blended kinda-risky cash flow.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why would that be?=C2=A0You could tell=C2=A0ps=
ychological=C2=A0stories, stories about conservative investors wanting safe=
 assets and aggressive investors wanting risky assets and nobody wanting st=
uff in the middle. But it is often useful to think about a story of=C2=A0<e=
m>ratings=C2=A0</em>and <em>regulation.=C2=A0</em>Schematically:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are a bank or an insurance compan=
y; you are in the business of taking money (deposits, premiums) from custom=
ers and investing it until they need it. You use the money to buy investmen=
t=C2=A0assets, and you make money=C2=A0if the assets return more money than=
 you need to give back to the customers. Your regulators require you to hav=
e a certain amount of capital: For every $100 of assets that you own, you c=
an have, say, $92 of deposits and $8 of your own money. The $8 is your capi=
tal.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But the regulators =E2=80=9Cr=
isk-weight=E2=80=9D your assets: Really, you need capital equal to 8% of yo=
ur risk-weighted assets, and different assets count differently. US Treasur=
y bills might get a 0% risk weight: You can buy $100 of Treasury bills with=
 $100 of deposits and $0 of capital. Business loans might get a 100% risk w=
eight: You need $8 of capital to buy $100 of loans. Bitcoin might get a <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30288429.269516/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTAvbWF5YmUt=
Z2FtZXN0b3AtaXMtZ29vZC1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl=
1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYW=
lnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB746eee11" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> 1,250% risk =
weight</a>: You need $100 of capital to buy $100 of Bitcoin; you can=E2=80=
=99t use depositor money at all.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Capital=C2=A0is, by general agree=
ment, expensive.=C2=A0All else equal, you would rather buy $100 of assets w=
ith $99 of deposits and $1 of your own money than with $80 of deposits and =
$20 of your own money. On the other hand, you=E2=80=99d rather buy higher-y=
ielding assets than lower-yielding assets. Higher-yielding assets are often=
 riskier, which means they have higher risk weights and require more capita=
l.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your job is to optimize this: Y=
ou want to get the highest=C2=A0yields with the lowest capital requirements=
. If there are two investments with the same risk and returns, but one of t=
hem has lower capital requirements, you should choose that one.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Someone offers you an attractive, kinda risky=
 investment. It has a 50% risk weight. If you buy $100 of it, it counts as =
$50 of risk-weighted assets, so you need $4=C2=A0of capital.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some financial engineer=C2=A0finds a way to slic=
e that investment into a very safe senior bond and a very risky equity inve=
stment. The slicing produces 80% senior bond and 20% risky equity. The seni=
or bond has a 0% risk weight =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s as good as Treasur=
y bills =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so requires $0 of capital. The very risky equity=
 has a 200% risk-weight: If you buy $20 of it, it counts as $40 of risk-wei=
ghted assets, so you need $3.20 of capital.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">You buy $80 of the safe bond and $20 of the risky equity, so you=
=C2=A0need a total of $3.20 of capital. You have saved $0.80 of capital.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But you bought the <em>same thing</e=
m>. You had $100 of stuff that required $4 of capital, you sliced it into a=
n $80 tranche and a $20 tranche, and somehow magically those two tranches a=
dd up to require $3.20 of capital.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not quite true that the story of the 200=
8 financial crisis is =E2=80=9Cinstead of making mortgage loans, holding th=
em, giving them a 50% risk weight and holding 4% capital against them, bank=
s made mortgage loans, sliced them up into securitizations, bought highly r=
ated tranches of them, and held much less capital against them,=E2=80=9D bu=
t it is kind of true, and worth keeping in mind.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly, if you are an insurance company, so=
me private equity=C2=A0 firm might come to you and ask you to invest $100 i=
n a private equity=C2=A0fund or a high-yield private credit fund. And you w=
ill say, sure, sounds great, but I am a regulated insurance company, and my=
 regulators prefer that I mostly invest my money in safe bonds. I can do so=
me private equity investing, but not <em>too=C2=A0</em>much; mostly I just =
buy bonds with good credit ratings.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then the PE firm will say: Okay, what if w=
e sliced our fund into junior and senior tranches? You can invest in both. =
The senior tranche is=C2=A0a=C2=A0<em>bond</em>, which pays back your money=
 with interest as long as our private equity fund doesn=E2=80=99t perform d=
isastrously. And the junior tranche is an=C2=A0<em>equity=C2=A0</em>upside =
stake, which pays back whatever the return on the fund is, minus whatever t=
he bond pays. You put, say, $80 into the bond and $20 into the equity stake=
.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is the same thing: Buying a whole stake i=
n the fund is economically identical to buying (1) a senior claim on the fu=
nd plus (2) a junior claim on the fund; you are just slicing up the cash fl=
ows. But now you can go to your regulator and say =E2=80=9Coh no it=E2=80=
=99s not $100 of equity; it=E2=80=99s $20 of equity and $80 of=C2=A0<em>bon=
ds</em>.=E2=80=9D Your regulator is much more comfortable with you buying b=
onds than buying equity, so you get better regulatory treatment and can do =
more of it. You go and get the bonds rated by a credit ratings firm, and fr=
om your regulator=E2=80=99s perspective you have transformed $100 of risky =
scary private equity investment into (1) $80 of safe A+ rated corporate bon=
ds plus (2) $20 of risky scary private equity investment.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/30288429.269516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMjgvZnR4LXMtYmxvY2tmaS1yZXNjdWUtZGlkbi10LXdvcms_Y21w=
aWQ9QkJEMDExODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3N=
sZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cCa2543315" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked a while back</a> about a form of this=
 trade, called a =E2=80=9Ccollateralized fund obligation,=E2=80=9D or CFO. =
(I am oversimplifying it: Often you don=E2=80=99t just slice up=C2=A0<em>on=
e=C2=A0</em>private equity investment; you put a bunch of different private=
 equity investments into a box and slice up their total cash flows.)=C2=A0Y=
esterday the Financial Times reported that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/30288429.269516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbn=
QvYjgyZGNhNDMtOWE5Mi00ZmMzLWFjYTgtZTQyNDVkNWNmNWYzP3NoYXJlVHlwZT1ub25naWZ0/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc0a3cb7e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> insurance regulators don=E2=80=
=99t like it</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US regulators are cracking down on investment =
vehicles used by private equity groups over fears that rating agencies are =
downplaying the products=E2=80=99 dangers, exposing insurers to undue risks=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The vehicles are known as =E2=80=9Ccollaterali=
sed fund obligations=E2=80=9D, a name that echoes the =E2=80=9Ccollateralis=
ed debt obligations=E2=80=9D that played a big role in the 2008 financial c=
risis. They parcel up stakes in hundreds of private equity-owned companies =
into products intended to diversify risk and so obtain better credit rating=
s.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A year-long investigation by the National Asso=
ciation of Insurance Commissioners, a US regulatory group, has found that r=
ating agencies can understate the risk of CFOs to insurers, which are among=
 the vehicles=E2=80=99 main investors, according to people familiar with th=
e matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The NAIC, which coordinates US insurance regul=
ators, has now decided to assess the risk of individual CFOs, supplanting c=
redit rating agencies =E2=80=94 a similar initiative to steps the regulator=
 took to rein in mortgage-backed securities in the wake of the financial cr=
isis.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The NAIC report is <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30288429.269516/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb250ZW50Lm5haWMub=
3JnL3NpdGVzL2RlZmF1bHQvZmlsZXMvaW5saW5lLWZpbGVzLzIwMjItMDE1LjAxJTIwVGFzayUy=
MEZvcmNlJTIwMjAyMiUyMEFtZW5kJTIwUFAlMjBTdHJ1Y3R1cmVkJTIwRXF1aXR5JTIwYW5kJTI=
wRnVuZHNWMTAuZG9jeA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBafd1d292" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here</a> (i=
n Microsoft Word download format, sorry), and it=C2=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=99t=
=C2=A0</em>exactly find =E2=80=9Cthat rating agencies can understate the ri=
sk of CFOs to insurers.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Instead, what it finds is that=C2=A0<=
em>this is too good of a regulatory arbitrage:</em></p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These investments are being reported as bonds =
and receiving a bond risk-based capital (RBC) factor based upon the mechani=
cal assignment of NAIC Designations that rely upon Credit Rating Provider (=
CRP) ratings through the filing exempt process. The use of CRP ratings woul=
d not be permitted for the fund or equity investments which underly these n=
otes if the equity or fund investment were held directly. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The structure may permit in-substance equity a=
nd fund investments to obtain improved RBC treatment than what would be rec=
eived if the investment had been directly reported. =C2=A0In addition to im=
proved RBC treatment, the structures could permit entities to hold more und=
erlying equity / fund investments than what would be permitted under state =
investment law. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Equity and fund investments that are structure=
d through another legal entity have been able to qualify as =E2=80=98bonds=
=E2=80=99 under the current definition due to their legal form (instead of =
substance as with the proposed bond definition) and bypass reporting requir=
ements for equity and fund investments. These structures have sometimes bee=
n referred to generically as =E2=80=9CRated Notes=E2=80=9D, but they may be=
 called other names. The name may change but the general framework is the s=
ame: an equity or fund investment is transformed into what the insurer repo=
rts as a bond through the insertion of an intervening entity, which issues =
a note that, due to a CRP rating, receives the statutory treatment of a bon=
d for accounting, reporting, RBC and NAIC Designation purposes. This proces=
s exploits the inherent weakness within the Filing Exempt process where any=
thing with a CRP rating is assumed to be a =E2=80=9Cbond=E2=80=9D and autom=
atically treated as such despite its underlying assets, structure, or risk.=
 =E2=80=A6</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It gives an example of an insurance company in=
vesting in a private credit fund that lends money to risky companies with B=
 credit ratings. Just investing directly in that fund is risky =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0it=E2=80=99s single-B credit investing =E2=80=94 and has high capital re=
quirements. But if you slice that fund into a 90% senior claim and a 10% ju=
nior claim, and then=C2=A0sell =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98investment units=E2=80=99 =
comprised of 90% Senior Notes and 10% limited partnership interest,=E2=80=
=9D the senior claim is safe, the junior claim is risky, and the combined =
=E2=80=9Cunit=E2=80=9D has a lower capital requirement than investing direc=
tly in the fund:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By investing in the investment uni=
ts issued by the Debt Feeder Fund, an insurer is able circumvent regulatory=
 guidance by transforming the Main Fund=E2=80=99s investments in =E2=80=9CB=
=E2=80=9D rated loans into a much higher rated note due to the intervening =
legal entity. =C2=A0An insurer investing in the investment unit (note and e=
quity) would be able to dramatically reduce its risk-based capital versus r=
eporting an LP Interest investment in the main fund holding =E2=80=9CB=E2=
=80=9D rated loans but be exposed to identical economic risk.=C2=A0=E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0The insurer making this investment could reduce its risk-based cap=
ital by 56.6%, an RBC factor reduction of 5.40%, if it invested in the inve=
stment unit (note and equity) with the note rated by a CRP instead of inves=
ting in the underlying assets directly while maintaining the exact same eco=
nomic exposure.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yep, that's the game!=C2=A0Finance is, in larg=
e part,=C2=A0about finding new ways to slice cash flows that will get bette=
r regulatory treatment than the old ways to slice cash flows. And financial=
 <em>regulation</em> is, in large part, about noticing the new ways that pe=
ople are slicing cash flows, and adjusting the regulations=C2=A0so that the=
 new ways get treated the same as the old ways. Or worse! Part of the goal =
here is logical consistency and treating economically similar things simila=
rly, but part of the goal is to=C2=A0<em>deter people from doing this</em>,=
 so the regulators might want to treat the new ways worse.</p>
