<![endif]-->
</div><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you were a normal=C2=A0customer at FT=
X, you were not allowed to have a negative balance in your account. If you =
put up $100 of money to buy $200 of crypto, and your crypto lost $50 of val=
ue, then your account balance was $50. If it lost another $50 of value, the=
n your balance was=C2=A0$0 and you were liquidated. Your account could neve=
r be worth -$10; you got liquidated before that.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you were a=C2=A0<em>market maker=C2=A0</em>=
on FTX, though, you=C2=A0<em>were=C2=A0</em>allowed to have a negative bala=
nce: Effectively, FTX would lend you the money so you could open a position=
 without depositing the money first, or have the market move against you wi=
thout instant liquidation.=C2=A0In FTX=E2=80=99s code, most accounts had a =
=E2=80=9Cborrow=E2=80=9D flag set to zero, meaning that they could not have=
 negative balances, but some 4,000 accounts had the borrow flag set to some=
 positive number, meaning that FTX would lend them the money up to some cre=
dit limit. Of those 4,000 accounts, 41=C2=A0had credit limits of $1 million=
 to $150 million. One =E2=80=94=C2=A0Alameda =E2=80=94=C2=A0had a higher li=
mit. Alameda=E2=80=99s limit was=C2=A0$65 billion. (Slide 18 shows a code s=
nippet, showing that the actual limit was $65,355,999,994.)=C2=A0=E2=80=9CF=
TX will allow Alameda to have a negative balance of up to $65 billion=E2=80=
=9D is functionally equivalent to =E2=80=9CAlameda can use as much of FTX=
=E2=80=99s customer money as it wants.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There was another flag in the code, though, =
=E2=80=9Ccan_withdraw_below_borrow.=E2=80=9D The =E2=80=9Cborrow=E2=80=9D f=
lag determines how negative your account can be and keep trading: If your b=
orrow flag is set to $10 million, and you put on some trades and they move =
against you and you end up with a balance of negative $5 million, then you =
can keep the trades on. But if you went to FTX and tried to cash out $4=C2=
=A0million to spend on groceries=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0giving you a total bal=
ance of negative $9=C2=A0million, still within your credit limit=C2=A0=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0FTX wouldn=E2=80=99t give you the money. You could use your cre=
dit limit to trade on FTX, but not to take out cash. =E2=80=9CNo, you still=
 owe us $5 million, pay us that first, we=E2=80=99re not letting you take a=
ny cash out before you pay us what you owe,=E2=80=9D FTX would quite reason=
ably say. Unless you had the =E2=80=9Ccan_withdraw_below_borrow=E2=80=9D fl=
ag set to =E2=80=9Ctrue.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Then FTX would say =E2=80=9Csure, he=
re=E2=80=99s the money.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One account had that flag set, says the presen=
tation: Alameda. To the tune of $65 billion. Setting the borrow flag to $65=
 billion and the can_withdraw_below_borrow flag to true is functionally equ=
ivalent to =E2=80=9CAlameda can take as much of FTX=E2=80=99s customer mone=
y as it wants, remove it from the exchange, and spend it on whatever.=E2=80=
=9D (Slides 16 and 17 give you a sense of what =E2=80=9Cwhatever=E2=80=9D m=
eant, including $253 million of Bahamas real estate =E2=80=94=C2=A0includin=
g $12.9 million for =E2=80=9CThe Conch Shack=E2=80=9D??? =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=
 $93 million of political donations.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The presentation describes this setting as =E2=
=80=9CGod Mode,=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0which I am not sure is a technical term found in FTX=E2=80=99s ac=
tual codebase or documentation, but you get the idea. FTX <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30288429.269516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9mZWF0dXJlcy8yMDIyLXRoZS1jcnlwdG8tc3RvcnktRlRYLWNvbGxhcHNlLW=
1hdHQtbGV2aW5lLz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTE4MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJ=
nV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMTgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5=
c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa7da3289" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  built a video game</a>=
 for other people to trade crypto, but FTX =E2=80=94=C2=A0or rather its aff=
iliate Alameda =E2=80=94=C2=A0had a cheat code. Everyone else got to trade =
crypto, and if they made money, they could take out the money that they mad=
e. Alameda got to trade crypto, and it got to take out as much money as it =
wanted, whether or not it made money. It was playing in God Mode.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But most of the presentation is about recoveri=
es: how much stuff FTX has found, what it thinks it=E2=80=99s worth, and ho=
w much it can pay to creditors. The headlines here are =E2=80=9CFTX Debtors=
 have identified approximately $5.5 billion of liquid assets to date,=E2=80=
=9D consisting of $1.7 billion of cash, $3.5 billion of =E2=80=9Cliquid cry=
pto currency and FTT tokens=E2=80=9D and $0.3 billion of securities. But =
=E2=80=9Cinvestigation has confirmed shortfalls at both International and U=
.S. Exchanges.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two points here. One is that we have <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30288429.269516/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMTIvanBtb3JnYW4t=
c2F5cy1mcmFuay13YXMtZnJhdWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl=
1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYW=
lnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB938666bf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  previously =
discussed</a> the importance of FTX US. Basically all the stuff above about=
 borrow flags and credit limits applies to=C2=A0what is sometimes called FT=
X International, FTX=E2=80=99s main exchange, which is based the Bahamas an=
d meant to serve non-US customers. FTX International is definitely insolven=
t; it loaned all that money to Alameda, which lost it. But FTX US is a sepa=
rate, tamer, more regulated business that was meant to serve US customers. =
It had much less in the way of margin and futures trading; in a loose sense=
 its business was just taking customers=E2=80=99 money, converting it into =
crypto, and holding the crypto for the customers. If FTX International is m=
issing customer money, then that can perhaps be explained as =E2=80=9Cit=E2=
=80=99s hard to run a futures exchange, we were extending credit to traders=
, and one trader blew up.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s a thing that happens in f=
inance sometimes, though obviously the =E2=80=9CGod Mode=E2=80=9D stuff is =
bad. But if FTX US is missing customer money =E2=80=94=C2=A0as FTX=E2=80=99=
s management says it is =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that can only really be theft.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so Sam Bankman-Fried, who is facing crimin=
al charges for blowing up FTX, has a strong interest in arguing that FTX US=
 is fine. Yesterday <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/30288429.269516/aHR0cHM6Ly9zYW1iZi5zdWJzdGFjay5jb20vcC9mdHgtdXMtYmFsYW5jZ=
S11cGRhdGUtMjAyMy0wMS0xNw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb90a4c66" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> he re=
plied to the FTX=E2=80=99s presentation on his Substack</a>, mainly to argu=
e that FTX US is still fine. Specifically:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the presentation that S&amp;C formally file=
d on the Delaware Chapter 11 court docket, S&amp;C failed to include $428m =
in FTX US=E2=80=99s bank accounts as an asset:</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">1. $181m of digital assets, not including $428=
m USD in banks</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">2. More than $181m of customer balances, inclu=
ding USD</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">3. Thus, they concluded that FTX US had a =E2=
=80=9Cshortfall=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Later in the same report, S&amp;C reveals that=
 FTX US has an additional $428m USD in bank accounts, on top of the $181m o=
f tokens=E2=80=94for roughly $609m of total assets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Customer balances are likely around $199m, and=
 certainly less than $497m (which they were a day earlier before massive wi=
thdrawals).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Thus FTX US had at least $111m, and likely aro=
und $400m, of excess cash on top of what was required to match customer bal=
ances.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose if FTX US customers had crypto balan=
ces of $200 million and FTX US had $180 million of crypto and $400 million =
of cash, that would be=C2=A0<em>weird=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0why wasn=E2=
=80=99t FTX US just holding all of their crypto in a box for them? isn=E2=
=80=99t that mismatch risky? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but more or less fine.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0What=E2=80=99s bad is if the customers had balances of $200 milli=
on and FTX US had only $180 million total; then you=E2=80=99d have to concl=
ude that the extra $20 million went missing in bad ways. Bankman-Fried argu=
es that it did not.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other point is that, when FTX was flounder=
ing into bankruptcy, I was rather harsh about Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s insis=
tence that its huge stash of FTT tokens was valuable. I wrote <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30288429.269516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC=
1zLWZ0eC1oYWQtYS1kZWF0aC1zcGlyYWwtYmVmb3JlLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwM=
TE4MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1=
dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMTgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cCa5fc3a8a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">  things like</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FTX issues a token called FTT. The attributes =
of this token are, like, it entitles you to some discounts and stuff, but t=
he main attribute is that FTX periodically uses a portion of its profits to=
 buy back FTT tokens. This makes FTT kind of like stock in FTX: The higher =
FTX=E2=80=99s profits are, the higher the price of FTT will be. It is not a=
ctually stock in FTX =E2=80=94 in fact FTX is a company and has stock and v=
enture capitalists bought it, etc. =E2=80=94 but it is a lot like stock in =
FTX. FTT is a bet on FTX=E2=80=99s future profits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it is also a crypto token, which means tha=
t a customer can come to [FTX] and post $100 worth of FTT as collateral and=
 borrow $50 worth of Bitcoin, or dollars, or whatever, against that collate=
ral, just as they would with any other token. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you think of the token as =E2=80=9Cmore or =
less stock,=E2=80=9D and you think of a crypto exchange as a securities bro=
ker-dealer, this is completely insane. If you go to an investment bank and =
say =E2=80=9Clend me $1 billion, and I will post $2 billion of your stock a=
s collateral,=E2=80=9D you are messing with very dark magic and they will s=
ay no. The problem with this is that it is wrong-way risk. (It is also, at =
least sometimes, illegal.) If people start to worry about the investment ba=
nk=E2=80=99s financial health, its stock will go down, which means that its=
 collateral will be less valuable, which means that its financial health wi=
ll get worse, which means that its stock will go down, etc. It is a death s=
piral.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/30288429.269516/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTQvZnR4LXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC13YXMtYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA=
xMTgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJn=
V0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDExOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB61d46f8c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> And</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is striking that the balance sh=
eet that FTX circulated to potential rescuers=C2=A0consisted=C2=A0<em>mostl=
y=C2=A0</em>of stuff it made up. Its balance sheet consisted mostly of stuf=
f it made up! Stuff it made up! You can=E2=80=99t do that!=C2=A0</p></block=
quote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing I will say about this harshness is t=
hat it is very context-dependent. In 2021, when FTT traded near $80 per tok=
en, and when FTX looked like a successful and widely respected crypto excha=
nge, it =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well,=C2=A0it would still have been a bad idea for F=
TX=C2=A0to=C2=A0<em>lend money to Alameda secured by FTT tokens</em>, fine,=
 but it would not have been crazy to say things like =E2=80=9CAlameda is wo=
rth many billions of dollars because of its huge stash of FTT tokens.=E2=80=
=9D The FTT tokens were valuable, the source of their value =E2=80=94 marke=
t confidence in FTX=E2=80=99s future cash flows and utility =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
seemed reasonable, Alameda had a lot of them, it=E2=80=99s all fine.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In November 2022,=C2=A0though, when FTX was hu=
rtling toward bankruptcy and Bankman-Fried was seeking rescue financing, I =
thought it was pretty weird for him to market Alameda=E2=80=99s stash of FT=
T tokens as being worth hundreds of millions of dollars. Once you are days =
from bankruptcy, you can=E2=80=99t expect to get hundreds of millions of do=
llars for=C2=A0<em>your stock</em>. Your stock is probably going to be wipe=
d out in bankruptcy. FTT is=C2=A0close enough to FTX stock that, in Novembe=
r 2022, FTX could not really count on getting much money for it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now it=E2=80=99s January 2023 and FTX is very =
much=C2=A0<em>in=C2=A0</em>bankruptcy and=C2=A0<em>still</em>, when FTX=E2=
=80=99s advisers list its $3.3 billion of liquid crypto assets, the second-=
biggest single holding (behind $685 million of Solana tokens) is $529 milli=
on of FTT. Those tokens are valuable to the extent that (1) FTX comes back =
as a popular exchange and the FTT tokens let holders get valuable discounts=
 on FTX fees and (2) FTX comes back as a popular exchange and uses some of =
its fee revenue to buy back FTT tokens. How likely are those outcomes? How =
likely do you think FTX=E2=80=99s bankruptcy advisers think those outcomes =
are? FTX is going around showing the world the code that allowed Alameda to=
 take all of its customers=E2=80=99 money. Confidence in FTX is not coming =
back, not if FTX=E2=80=99s current managers have anything to say about it. =
They are=C2=A0going to have a hard time shopping their stash of FTT tokens.=
 The explanation undermines the recovery.</p>
