 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Company leaders have told some managers that e=
mployees who receive a =E2=80=9Cmeets all expectations=E2=80=9D grade in th=
eir performance review have to up their game, said a current manager. In th=
e past, employees receiving such a grade were told that was a positive sign=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The new message comes amid one of the most int=
ense performance-review cycles in the company=E2=80=99s history, in which M=
eta managers are ratcheting up pressure on the workforce. It follows Meta=
=E2=80=99s layoff of 13% of its workforce, or 11,000 people, in November. N=
ow, as fears of a recession mount, some employees worry more job cuts could=
 be on the horizon.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is semantically irritating =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0shouldn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cmeets <em>all</em> expectations=E2=80=9D incl=
ude meeting the meta-expectation that you exceed the other expectations? =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but practically reasonable; the message is =E2=80=9Cyou have=
 to blow us away every day if you want to keep working here,=E2=80=9D which=
 is a nice thing to aspire to.=C2=A0(Also I mean, fine, grade inflation is =
everywhere.) Incidentally Meta=E2=80=99s highest performance grade (above =
=E2=80=9Cexceeds expectations=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cgreatly exceeds expecta=
tions=E2=80=9D) is =E2=80=9Credefines expectations,=E2=80=9D which I am not=
 sure is entirely a good thing. =E2=80=9CThis person makes me expect things=
 I had never expected before=E2=80=9D: Could go either way.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I was going to make a joke about how it is har=
d to run a company where you fire=C2=A0your=C2=A0average employees every ye=
ar, but actually that seems plausible=C2=A0in big tech in 2023? Like, you h=
ave 90,000 employees, you rank them, you fire the bottom 50,000, now you ha=
ve 40,000 employees, you rank them next year, you fire the bottom 25,000, n=
ow you have 15,000 employees, you rank them the next year, you fire the bot=
tom 8,000, etc., I don=E2=80=99t know, the Elon Musk Twitter experience tea=
ches that you can repeatedly fire half of your workforce and it might be fi=
ne, or fine-ish.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Speaking of the Elon Musk Twitter experience, =
Twitter is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3028842=
