ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> New York Magazine cover story</a>=
 about Musk=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cextremely hardcore=E2=80=9D regime at Twitte=
r that I found kind of upsetting to read? Like I feel like there are, in th=
e world, cushy jobs, and there are hardcore jobs, and some people want hard=
core jobs building rockets for SpaceX and other people want cushy jobs sell=
ing ads at Twitter. And if you start a company, you can start a hardcore co=
mpany or a cushy company or something in between, but if there=E2=80=99s an=
 already-existing large public company it is very hard to transition it fro=
m one end of the scale to another.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0When you select yourself into a cushy job and it suddenly, throug=
h the market for corporate control, becomes hardcore, that=E2=80=99s pretty=
 rough on you. Apparently thousands of Twitter employees who six months ago=
 were working reasonable hours for good pay with great snacks have decided =
=E2=80=9Cokay guess I=E2=80=99ll be sleeping at the office from now on,=E2=
=80=9D but presumably thousands of others had arranged their lives in such =
a way that they had to go home and see their families at night? I just don=
=E2=80=99t understand how you can take a cushy company=C2=A0and turn it har=
dcore without replacing all the employees and giving the new employees some=
thing inspiring to be hardcore <em>about</em>.</p>
